  <div class="stackedit__html"><h1 id="introduction-to-json">Introduction to JSON</h1>
<ul>
<li>JSON: <strong>J</strong>ava<strong>S</strong>cript <strong>O</strong>bject <strong>N</strong>otation.</li>
<li>JSON is a syntax for storing and exchanging data.</li>
<li>JSON is text, written with JavaScript object notation.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="syntax">Syntax</h2>
<p>The JSON syntax is a subset of the JavaScript syntax.</p>
<h3 id="rules">Rules</h3>
<ul>
<li>Data is in name/value pairs</li>
<li>Data is separated by commas</li>
<li>Curly braces hold objects</li>
<li>Square brackets hold arrays</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="values">Values</h2>
<ul>
<li>a string</li>
<li>a number</li>
<li>an object (JSON object)</li>
<li>an array</li>
<li>a boolean</li>
<li>null</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="json-files">JSON Files</h2>
<ul>
<li>The file type for JSON files is “.json”</li>
<li>The MIME type for JSON text is “application/json”</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="json-and-php">JSON and PHP</h2>
<p>Objects and arrays in PHP can be converted into JSON by using the PHP function<code>json_encode()</code></p>
<pre class=" language-php"><code class="prism  language-php"><span class="token php language-php"><span class="token delimiter important">&lt;?php</span>  
<span class="token variable">$myArr</span> <span class="token operator">=</span> <span class="token punctuation">[</span><span class="token string">"John"</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span> <span class="token string">"Mary"</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span> <span class="token string">"Peter"</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span> <span class="token string">"Sally"</span><span class="token punctuation">]</span><span class="token punctuation">;</span>  
<span class="token variable">$myJSON</span> <span class="token operator">=</span> <span class="token function">json_encode</span><span class="token punctuation">(</span><span class="token variable">$myArr</span><span class="token punctuation">)</span><span class="token punctuation">;</span>  
<span class="token keyword">echo</span> <span class="token variable">$myJSON</span><span class="token punctuation">;</span>  
<span class="token delimiter important">?&gt;</span></span>
</code></pre>
<p>Convert JSON string to PHP arrays using <code>json_decode()</code></p>
<pre class=" language-php"><code class="prism  language-php"><span class="token php language-php"><span class="token delimiter important">&lt;?php</span>

<span class="token variable">$mySampleJson</span> <span class="token operator">=</span> <span class="token string">'{
	"fruits": [
		{
			"name": "apple",
			"color": "red"
		}, 
		{
			"name": "papaya",
			"color": "orange",		
		}
	]
}'</span><span class="token punctuation">;</span>


<span class="token variable">$array</span> <span class="token operator">=</span> <span class="token function">json_decode</span><span class="token punctuation">(</span><span class="token variable">$mySampleJson</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span> <span class="token boolean">true</span><span class="token punctuation">)</span><span class="token punctuation">;</span>
<span class="token function">print_r</span><span class="token punctuation">(</span><span class="token variable">$array</span><span class="token punctuation">)</span><span class="token punctuation">;</span>

</span></code></pre>
<p><strong>Note</strong>: Note of the 2nd parameter of <code>json_encode</code>, if you want the result to be an array, always set to true. Otherwise, the result will be a PHP object.</p>
